BENEFIT YOUTH ARTS PROGRAMMING\n\nPRESS RELEASE\n\nDAVID HIDALGO / LOS CENZONTLES REUNITE FOR RARE LIVE PERFORMANCE\n \nLegendary guitarist, singer, composer David Hidalgo, known best for his work with Los Lobos, reunites with Mexican roots band Los Cenzontles (The Mockingbirds) for a rare live performance in their Music & Tamales series.\nFRIDAY, MARCH 4 AT 8 PM\nLOS CENZONTLES MEXICAN ARTS CENTER - 13108 SAN PABLO AVE, SAN PABLO, CA 94805\nGENERAL ADMISSION $35 – TAMALES Y BEBIDAS AVAILABLE!\n510-233-8015 - ONLINE TICKETS http://www.themockingbirds.info/store/specials.php\n \nDavid Hidalgo and Los Cenzontles have recorded two critically acclaimed full length albums in the past three years, American Horizon and Songs of Wood & Steel.\n \n“David is a legend among musicians,” said Eugene Rodriguez, leader of Los Cenzontles.  “We share a long friendship and our lives have numerous parallels.   David and Los Lobos are from the tough urban center of East Los Angeles and Los Cenzontles are from another, the streets of San Pablo/Richmond, so we are brothers.   He is at the top of his game, yet has maintained his humility and humanity.  It’s an honor for us that he has taken this time to play with us.“\n \nLos Cenzontles was formed by Rodriguez in 1989 as a youth group which developed into a training program for neighborhood youth in traditional Mexican roots music, dance and arts.  The group has recorded numerous CDs. Among their collaborators are a host of Mexican roots musicians and innovative traditionalists such as Ry Cooder, The Chieftains, Linda Ronstadt and Los Lobosamong others.\n \nWhen asked about Los Cenzontles commitment to keeping Mexican musical traditions alive, Hildago said,   “What they are doing is beautiful for the community and it’s out of love and respect for the culture and the legacy of the music. It is really important and I am happy to do whatever I can to keep it going.”\n \nPRESS NOTES:\n‘The songs, in English and Spanish, are about love, immigration, searching for work and a higher purpose, and they dip into Mexican styles like cumbia, son Jarocho and banda along with 12-bar blues and soul shuffles. But the songs are never preservationist, much less didactic. It’s the flexible, hard-nosed, impure music of people gleaning pleasure where they can, on new ground and in tough times.’\nJon Pareles, New York Times\n \n‘… a rich blend of folk music and searing blues guitar. Occasional detours into improvisational jam-band fare exhibit the group’s ability to deliver the expected and the unexpected with equal grace.’  \nNate Seltenrich, East Bay Express\n \n‘It’s hard to imagine a modern player who has created a more satisfying musical legacy than David Hidalgo. Songs Of Wood & Steel is yet another fine example of his magic touch.’\nPaul Epstein, Twist and Shout\n \n‘Beautiful stuff.’ Dan Forte, Vintage Guitar","artists":[{"id":4677,"name":"Los
